u/weekly/ssp/sng_nac_89.php?reg=15 \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f Weekly - \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0441\u043e\u044e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 1989 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c \u0421\u0421\u0421\u0420] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604054915/http://demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/sng_nac_89.php?reg=15 |date=June 4, 2011 }}</ref> The majority of Armenians live in [[Tallinn]]: 58% in the year 2000.<ref name=\"2000census\" />\n\nWith the affirmation of Estonia's independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, Soviet-era immigrants and their Estonian-born children were not granted citizenship automatically.\n\nA football club based in Tallinn, [[FC Ararat Tallinn]], is named after the mountain [[Mount Ararat|Ararat]] and has a partnership with the Armenian club [[FC Ararat Yerevan]].\n\n==Latvia==\nArmenians in [[Latvia]] number around 5,000 according to armeniandiaspora.com<ref name=\"ArmenianDiaspora website\">[http://www.armeniadiaspora.com/population.html ArmenianDiaspora website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511084353/http://www.armeniadiaspora.com/population.html |date=May 11, 2013 }}</ref> and 2,742 according to Latvian yearly statistics of 2008.<ref>[http://www.pmlp.gov.lv/lv/documents/statistika/IRD/ISVN_Latvija_pec_TTB_VPD.pdf Population of Latvia by ethnicity and citizenship, 01.07.2008.]{{in lang|lv}}</ref>\nThe Armenians live mainly in [[Riga]].\n\nIn 1887 had established Latvian Armenian Society. One Armenian was reported in the [[J\u00e4ger Report]] as murdered by [[Einsatzgruppe A]] in [[Daugavpils]] in 1941.<ref>[http://fcit.usf.edu/holocaust/resource/document/DocJager.htm