was due mainly to the needs of trade, although from the historical sources it is known, that Armenian school was established in 16th century Vilnius, Armenian guild in the 16th to 18th centuries Vilnius.<ref>[http://lietuva-armenija.lt/?p=27] History of Armenians in Lithuania {{in lang|lt}}</ref> One of the most prominent painter of the 19th century in Lithuania was [[Jan Rustem]] (Armenian: \u0545\u0561\u0576 \u054c\u0578\u0582\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0574). The history of most of the Armenian community now living in Lithuania mainly occurs in the 20th century.\n\n==Famous Baltic Armenians==\n\n* [[Vladimir Gasparyan]]\n* [[Boris Parsadanian]]\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Armenia-Lithuania relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.li.lv/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=102&Itemid=1119 Eastern Minorities]//Latvian Institute\n*[http://www.armenianow.com/?action=viewArticle&IID=1040&CID=1239&AID=1046&lng=eng Baltic \u201cyans\u201d: A visit with the Armenians of Latvia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111002155550/http://noev-kovcheg.1gb.ru/article.asp?n=70&a=18 \u0410\u0440\u043c\u044f\u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u041b\u0430\u0442\u0432\u0438\u0438. \u041e\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u2014 \u043a \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0435]\n\n{{Armenian diaspora}}\n{{Immigration to Lithuania}}\n\n[[Category:Armenian diaspora in Europe|Baltic states]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Estonia]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Latvia]]\n", "name_user": "Estopedist1", "label": "safe", "comment": "reference fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armenians_in_the_Baltic_states"}
{"title_page": "Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish gynecologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name =  Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m\n| image = Widerstr\u00f6m, Karolina ur Cedersch\u00f6ld; En banbryterska (1913).jpg\n| caption = Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m\n| residence = \n| other_names =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1856|12|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Helsingborg, Sweden\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1949|3|4|1856|12|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality   = Swedish\n| alma_mater    = Karolinska Institutet\n| known = the first female physician with a university education\n| occupation = doctor and gynecologist\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Karolina Olivia Widerstr\u00f6m''' (10 December 1856 \u2013 4 March 1949), was a Swedish doctor and [[gynecologist]]. She was the first female physician with a university education in her country. She was also a feminist and a politician, and engaged in the questions of sexual education and female suffrage. She was chairwoman of the [[National Association for Women's Suffrage (Sweden)|National Association for Women's Suffrage]] and a member of the Stockholm city council.\n\n== Biography ==\n[[File:Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m 001.jpg|thumb|left|Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m]]\n\nKarolina Widerstr\u00f6m was the daughter of the gymnastic teacher and veterinarian Otto Fredrik Widerstr\u00f6m and Olivia Erika Dill\u00e9n. The family moved to Stockholm in 1873.\n\n===Education===\nWomen were officially admitted to the universities in Sweden in 1870. Her father wished for her to be a gymnastic teacher like himself. In 1873\u20131875, Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m was a student at the [[Swedish School of Sport and Health Sciences|Royal Central Gymnastics Institute]], and in 1875\u20131877, she was the assistant to Professor Branting. She was also active as a medical gymnast. In 1879, she received her exam at ''[[Wallinska skolan]]'' and in 1880 her exam in medical philosophy at the university at Uppsala. In May 1884, she received her medical exam at the ''[[Karolinska Institutet]]'' in Stockholm.\n\n===Medical career===\nWiderstr\u00f6m wanted women and girls to know more about their own bodies, to dress more healthily, and to receive the same rights and possibilities as men. She was especially active within gynecology and women's health.  Her best-known work within her field was ''Kvinnohygien'' ('Women's hygiene'), which was first published in 1899, and reprinted in seven editions until 1932.\n\n===Activism===\n\nConcerned for women's health issued, she was a strong supporter of the [[Svenska dr\u00e4gtreformf\u00f6reningen|Swedish Dress Reform Association]] and a vocal force in writing medical articles advocating against [[corset controversy|tight laced corsets]], which at this point in time was a serious health issue.<ref>Bagerius, Henric.. Korsettkriget : modeslaveri och kvinnokamp vid f\u00f6rra sekelskiftet (F\u00f6rsta utg\u00e5van, f\u00f6rsta tryckningen). {{ISBN|978-91-27-15169-7}}. OCLC 1112090542</ref>\n\nFrom about 1900, Widerstr\u00f6m was active in the struggle to abolish the so-called reglementation of prostitutes, that is to say the forced registration and regular examination for venereal diseases of prostitutes, a system highly debated among women's rights activists at the time, which organized in the ''[[Svenska Federationen]]'' to oppose it.\n\n===Political engagement===\nKarolina Widstr\u00f6m was elected to the Stockholm city council in 1912 for the liberals, where she served until 1915. She was elected chairwoman of the Swedish Society for Woman Suffrage in 1918, one year before the women suffrage was granted in Sweden in 1919, and became its last chairwoman when she stepped down after the organisation was dissolved in 1921, when the purpose of the organisation was fulfilled and both genders exercised the right to vote in the 1921 election.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Charlotte Yhlen]] first female Swedish physician who graduated from a university (though in this case, abroad)\n* [[Hedda Andersson]] second female physician in Sweden\n* [[Emmy Rappe]] first educated Swedish nurse\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* Lena Hammarberg, ''Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m \u2013 sexualreformator och f\u00f6reningskvinna''\n* ''Ny svensk historia: [[Oscar II]] och hans tid, 1872\u20131907'', [[Erik Lindorm]] 1936 s.231\n* ''Sveriges befolkning 1890'', ([[CD-ROM]]) [[National Archives of Sweden|Riksarkivet]] 2003\n* [http://www.ub.gu.se/kvinn/portaler/rostratt/biografier/ R\u00f6str\u00e4tt, biografier]\n* Lundberg, Anna (2008). L\u00e4karnas blanka vapen: svensk smittskyddslagstiftning i historiskt perspektiv. L\u00e4karnas blanka vapen: svensk smittskyddslagstiftning i historiskt perspektiv. Sid. 85. {{ISBN|978-91-85509-08-9}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widerstrom, Karolina}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish gynaecologists]]\n[[Category:Women gynaecologists]]\n[[Category:Swedish suffragists]]\n[[Category:Swedish women physicians]]\n[[Category:Swedish women in politics]]\n[[Category:Local political office-holders in Sweden]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swedish physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish gynecologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name =  Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m\n| image = Widerstr\u00f6m, Karolina ur Cedersch\u00f6ld; En banbryterska (1913).jpg\n| caption = Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m\n| residence = \n| other_names =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1856|12|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Helsingborg, Sweden\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1949|3|4|1856|12|10|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| nationality   = Swedish\n| alma_mater    = Karolinska Institutet\n| known = the first female physician with a university education\n| occupation = doctor and gynecologist\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Karolina Olivia Widerstr\u00f6m''' (10 December 1856 \u2013 4 March 1949), was a Swedish doctor and [[gynecologist]]. She was the first female physician with a university education in her country. She was also a feminist and a politician, and engaged in the questions of sexual education and female suffrage. She was chairwoman of the [[National Association for Women's Suffrage (Sweden)|National Association for Women's Suffrage]] and a member of the Stockholm city council.\n\n== Biography ==\n[[File:Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m 001.jpg|thumb|left|Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m]]\n\nKarolina Widerstr\u00f6m was the daughter of the gymnastic teacher and veterinarian Otto Fredrik Widerstr\u00f6m and Olivia Erika Dill\u00e9n. The family moved to Stockholm in 1873.\n\n===Education===\nWomen were officially admitted to the universities in Sweden in 1870. Her father wished for her to be a gymnastic teacher like himself. In 1873\u20131875, Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m was a student at the [[Swedish School of Sport and Health Sciences|Royal Central Gymnastics Institute]], and in 1875\u20131877, she was the assistant to Professor Branting. She was also active as a medical gymnast. In 1879, she received her exam at ''[[Wallinska skolan]]'' and in 1880 her exam in medical philosophy at the university at Uppsala. In May 1884, she received her medical exam at the ''[[Karolinska Institutet]]'' in Stockholm.\n\n===Medical career===\nWiderstr\u00f6m wanted women and girls to know more about their own bodies, to dress more healthily, and to receive the same rights and possibilities as men. She was especially active within gynecology and women's health.  Her best-known work within her field was ''Kvinnohygien'' ('Women's hygiene'), which was first published in 1899, and reprinted in seven editions until 1932. \n\n===Activism===\n\nConcerned for women's health issued, she was a strong supporter of the [[Svenska dr\u00e4gtreformf\u00f6reningen|Swedish Dress Reform Association]] and a vocal force in writing medical articles advocating against [[corset controversy|tight laced corsets]], which at this point in time was a serious health issue.<ref>Bagerius, Henric.. Korsettkriget : modeslaveri och kvinnokamp vid f\u00f6rra sekelskiftet (F\u00f6rsta utg\u00e5van, f\u00f6rsta tryckningen). {{ISBN|978-91-27-15169-7}}. OCLC 1112090542</ref>\n\nFrom about 1900, Widerstr\u00f6m was active in the struggle to abolish the so-called reglementation of prostitutes, that is to say the forced registration and regular examination for venereal diseases of prostitutes, a system highly debated among women's rights activists at the time, which organized in the ''[[Svenska Federationen]]'' to oppose it.\n\n===Political engagement===\nKarolina Widstr\u00f6m was elected to the Stockholm city council in 1912 for the liberals, where she served until 1915. She was elected chairwoman of the Swedish Society for Woman Suffrage in 1918, one year before the women suffrage was granted in Sweden in 1919, and became its last chairwoman when she stepped down after the organisation was dissolved in 1921, when the purpose of the organisation was fulfilled and both genders exercised the right to vote in the 1921 election.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Charlotte Yhlen]] first female Swedish physician who graduated from a university (though in this case, abroad)\n* [[Hedda Andersson]] second female physician in Sweden\n* [[Emmy Rappe]] first educated Swedish nurse\n\n== Sources ==\n* Lena Hammarberg, ''Karolina Widerstr\u00f6m \u2013 sexualreformator och f\u00f6reningskvinna''\n* ''Ny svensk historia: [[Oscar II]] och hans tid, 1872\u20131907'', [[Erik Lindorm]] 1936 s.231\n* ''Sveriges befolkning 1890'', ([[CD-ROM]]) [[National Archives of Sweden|Riksarkivet]] 2003\n* [http://www.ub.gu.se/kvinn/portaler/rostratt/biografier/ R\u00f6str\u00e4tt, biografier]\n* Lundberg, Anna (2008). L\u00e4karnas blanka vapen: svensk smittskyddslagstiftning i historiskt perspektiv. L\u00e4karnas blanka vapen: svensk smittskyddslagstiftning i historiskt perspektiv. Sid. 85. {{ISBN|978-91-85509-08-9}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widerstrom, Karolina}}\n[[Category:1856 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:Swedish gynaecologists]]\n[[Category:Women gynaecologists]]\n[[Category:Swedish suffragists]]\n[[Category:Swedish women physicians]]\n[[Category:Swedish women in politics]]\n[[Category:Local political office-holders in Sweden]]\n[[Category:19th-century Swedish physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Swedish physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century women physicians]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karolina_Widerstr%C3%B6m"}
{"title_page": "Schengen Area", "text_new": "{{redirect|Schengen}}\n{{about|the European border control-free travel area|free movement of goods and services in the EEA|European Single Market}}\n{{short description|Area of 26 European states without mutual border controls}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox|title = Schengen Area\n|image          = [[File:Map of the Schengen Area.svg|250px|alt=The Schengen Area]]\n|caption        = Map of Europe <div style=\"text-align: left;\">{{legend|#003399|Member states}}{{legend|#27a4bb|Countries ''de facto'' participating}}{{legend|#ffa500|Members of the EU legally obliged to join the Schengen area, but not yet members}}</div>\n|label1         = Policy of\n|data1          = {{flag|European Union}}\n|label2         = Type\n|data2          = [[Open border]]s area\n|label3         = Established\n|data3          = 1995\n|label4         = Members\n|data4          = {{Collapsible list|titlestyle=font-weight:normal; background:transparent; text-align:left;|title=26 states|{{flaglist|Austria}}|{{flaglist|Belgium|state}}|{{flaglist|Czech Republic}}|{{flaglist|Denmark}}|{{flaglist|Estonia}}|{{flaglist|Finland}}|{{flaglist|France}}|{{flaglist|Germany}}|{{flaglist|Greece}}|{{flaglist|Hungary}}|{{flaglist|Iceland}}|{{flaglist|Italy}}|{{flaglist|Latvia}}|{{flaglist|Liechtenstein}}|{{flaglist|Lithuania}}|{{flaglist|Luxembourg}}|{{flaglist|Malta}}|{{flaglist|Netherlands}}|{{flaglist|Norway}}|{{flaglist|Poland}}|{{flaglist|Portugal}}|{{flaglist|Slovakia}}|{{flaglist|Slovenia}}|{{flaglist|Spain}}|{{flaglist|Sweden}}|{{flaglist|Switzerland}}}}\n|label5          = Area\n|data5           = {{convert|4,312,099|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n|label6          = Population\n|data6           = 419,392,429\n|label7          = Density\n|data7           = 97/km<sup>2</sup>\n|label8          = [[GDP]] (Nominal)\n|data8           = US$15 trillion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://knoema.com//IMFWEO2016Apr/imf-world-economic-outlook-weo-april-2016|title=IMF World Economic Outlook (WEO), April 2016 - knoema.com|website=Knoema}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Politics of the European Union}}\n\nThe '''Schengen Area''' ({{IPAc-en|pron|\u02c8|\u0283|\u025b|\u014b|\u0259n}}) is an area comprising 26 [[Europe]]an states that have officially abolished all passport and all other types of [[border control]] at their mutual borders. The area mostly functions as a single jurisdiction for international travel purposes, with a common [[visa policies in the European Union|visa policy]]. The area is named after the 1985 [[Schengen Agreement]] signed in [[Schengen, Luxembourg]]. \n\nOf the 27 EU [[member states of the European Union|member states]], 22 participate in the Schengen Area. Of the five EU members that are not part of the Schengen Area, four\u2014[[Bulgaria and the European Union|Bulgaria]], [[Croatia and the European Union|Croatia]], [[Cyprus and the European Union|Cyprus]], and [[Romania and the European Union|Romania]]\u2014are legally obliged to join the area in the future, while the other one\u2014[[Ireland and the European Union|Ireland]]\u2014maintains an [[opt-outs in the European Union|opt-out]]. The four [[European Free Trade Association]] (EFTA) member states, [[Iceland and the European Union|Iceland]], [[Liechtenstein and the European Union|Liechtenstein]], [[Norway and the European Union|Norway]], and [[Switzerland and the European Union|Switzerland]], are not members of the EU, but have signed agreements in association with the Schengen Agreement. Three [[European microstates]] that are not members of the European Union but which are enclaves or semi-enclave within an EU member state\u2014[[Monaco and the European Union|Monaco]], [[San Marino and the European Union|San Marino]], and [[Vatican City and the European Union|Vatican City]]\u2014are ''[[de facto]]'' part of the Schengen Area.\n\nThe Schengen Area has a population of over 420&nbsp;million people and an area of {{convert|4312099|km2|sqmi|0}}.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://biblio.ucv.ro/bib_web/bib_pdf/EU_books/0056.pdf |title=The Schengen Area |date=12 December 2008 |publisher=European Commission |isbn=978-92-79-15835-3 |doi=10.2758/45874 |accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref> About 1.7 million people commute to work across a European border each day, and in some regions these people constitute up to a third of the workforce. Each year, there are 1.3 billion crossings of Schengen borders in total. 57 million crossings are due to transport of goods by road, with a value of \u20ac2.8 trillion each year.<ref name=\"europarl\"/><ref name=\"ECFR\">{{cite web |title=The Future of Schengen |author=European Council on Foreign Relations |date=2016 |accessdate=2017-06-15 |url=http://www.ecfr.eu/specials/scorecard/schengen_flash_scorecard}}</ref><ref name=\"barriers\">{{cite journal |title=Schengen's economic impact: Putting up barriers |journal=The Economist |date=2016-02-06| accessdate=2017-06-15 |url=https://www.economist.com/news/briefing/21690065-permanent-reintroduction-border-controls-would-harm-trade-europe-putting-up-barriers}}</ref> The decrease in the cost of trade due to Schengen varies from 0.42% to 1.59% depending on geography, trade partners, and other factors. Countries outside of the Schengen area also benefit.<ref name=\"CEPR\"/> States in the Schengen Area have strengthened border controls with non-Schengen countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=The refugee crisis: Fixing Schengen is not enough |url=https://www.cer.eu/insights/refugee-crisis-fixing-schengen-not-enough |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==History==\n{{Main|Schengen Agreement}}\n\nThe Schengen Agreement was signed on 14 June 1985 by five of the ten [[Member states of the European Union|EC member states]]<ref name=\"BBCWorld\">{{citation |title=Fortress Europe |publisher=BBC World Service |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/theneweurope/wk22.htm}}</ref> in the town of [[Schengen, Luxembourg]]. The Schengen Area was established separately from the [[European Communities]], when consensus could not be reached among all EC member states on the abolition of border controls.\n\nThe Agreement was supplemented in 1990 by the Schengen Convention, which proposed the abolition of internal border controls and a common visa policy.<ref name=\"Baltic Legal\">{{citation |title=Schengen area by Latvian Law Firm |publisher=Baltic Legal|url=http://www.immigration-residency.eu/counsel/schengen-area/}}</ref> The Agreements and the rules adopted under them were entirely separate from the [[Institutions of the European Union|EC structures]], and led to the creation of the Schengen Area on 26 March 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://biblio.ucv.ro/bib_web/bib_pdf/EU_books/0056.pdf |title=The Schengen Area |publisher=European Commission |accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs more EU member states signed the Schengen Agreement, consensus was reached on absorbing it into the procedures of the EU. The Agreement and its related conventions were incorporated into the mainstream of [[European Union law]] by the [[Amsterdam Treaty]] in 1997, which came into effect in 1999. A consequence of the Agreement being part of European law is that any amendment or regulation is made within its processes, in which the non-EU members are not participants. The UK and Ireland have operated a [[Common Travel Area]] (CTA) since 1923 (with passport-free travel and freedom of movement with each other), but the UK would not abolish border controls with any other counties and therefore opted out of the Agreement. While not signing the Schengen Treaty, Ireland has always looked more favourably on joining, but has not done so in order to maintain the CTA and its open border with [[Northern Ireland]].<ref>[http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/0450/D.0450.199503140014.html Minister for Justice, Nora Owen, ''D\u00e1il Debates'' volume 450 column 1171 (14 March 1995)]; [http://historical-debates.oireachtas.ie/D/0501/D.0501.199903090246.htmlMinister for Justice, John O'Donoghue, ''D\u00e1il Debates'' volume 501 column 1506 (9 March 1999)]{{dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}; \"Declaration by Ireland on Article 3 of the Protocol on the position of the United Kingdom and Ireland\" attached to the Treaty of Amsterdam.</ref> The Nordic members required Norway and Iceland to be included, which was accepted, so a consensus could be reached.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\n== Membership ==\n=== Current members ===\n{{Schengen Agreement Labelled Map 2}}\n\nThe Schengen Area consists of 26 states, including four which are not members of the [[European Union]] (EU). Two of the non-EU members{{snd}}Iceland and Norway{{snd}}are part of the [[Nordic Passport Union]] and are officially classified as 'states associated with the Schengen activities of the EU'.<ref name=\"associated-states\"/> Switzerland was allowed to participate in the same manner in 2008. Liechtenstein joined the Schengen Area on 19 December 2011.<ref name=\"Liechtenstein\">{{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/homepage/showfocus?lang=en&focusID=78856 |title=Liechtenstein to join Schengen |publisher=Council of the European Union |year=2011}}</ref> ''De facto'', the Schengen Area also includes three European micro-states{{snd}}Monaco, San Marino and the Vatican City{{snd}}that maintain open or semi-open borders with other Schengen member countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swifttourism.com/visit-europe.html |title=Tourist, Student and Work visa to Europe |publisher=Swift Tourism |year=2010}}</ref>\n\nOne EU member state{{snd}}Ireland{{snd}}negotiated opt-outs from Schengen and continues to operate border controls with other EU member states, while at the same time being part of the [[Common Travel Area]] with the United Kingdom (a [[Brexit|former EU member]]). The remaining four EU member states{{snd}}Bulgaria, Croatia, Cyprus and Romania{{snd}}are obliged to eventually join the Schengen Area. However, before fully implementing the Schengen rules, each state must have its preparedness assessed in four areas: [[Controlled airspace|air borders]], [[visa (document)|visas]], police cooperation, and [[Information privacy|personal data protection]]. This evaluation process involves a questionnaire and visits by EU experts to selected institutions and workplaces in the country under assessment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/legislation_summaries/justice_freedom_security/free_movement_of_persons_asylum_immigration/l33020_en.htm |title=The Schengen Area and cooperation |publisher=europa.eu |date=2009-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe only land borders with border controls (not counting temporary ones) between EU/EEA members, are those of Bulgaria, Croatia and Romania (which are expected to be removed at a future date).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=uriserv:OJ.C_.2018.261.01.0006.01.ENG&toc=OJ:C:2018:261:TOC |title=Update of the list of border crossing points as referred to in Article 2(8) of Regulation (EU) 2016/399 of the European Parliament and of the Council on a Union Code on the rules governing the movement of persons across borders (Schengen Borders Code) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=25 July 2018  |website= europa.eu |publisher=European Union |access-date= |quote= |language= |trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"250\" |State\n! Area<br/><small>(km<sup>2</sup>)</small>\n! Population{{UN_Population|ref}}<br/>({{UN_Population|Year}})\n! Signed{{refn|The original agreement, a subsequent protocol extending the agreement to the state, an agreement on accession to the EU, or agreement on association with the Schengen acquis.|group=Note}}\n! Date of first<br/>implementation{{refn|Of the provisions related to the elimination of border controls. In some cases the provisions related to the [[Schengen Information System]] were applied earlier.|group=Note}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Austria}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{nts|83871}}\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |{{UN_Population|Austria}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|1995|4|28}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://verdragenbank.overheid.nl/en/Treaty/Details/006127.html |title=Protocol on the accession of the Government of the Republic of Austria to the Agreement between the Governments of the Member States of the Benelux Economic Union, the Federal Republic of Germany and the French Republic on the gradual abolition of controls at their common borders, signed at Schengen on 14 June 1985, as amended by the Protocols of 27 November 1990, 25 June 1991 and 6 November 1992 on the accession of the Governments of the Italian Republic, the Kingdom of Spain and the Portuguese Republic and the Hellenic Republic, respectively |accessdate=2014-10-31 |publisher=Government of the Netherlands}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|1997|12|1}}<ref name=austria>{{cite web |url=https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/GeltendeFassung.wxe?Abfrage=Bundesnormen&Gesetzesnummer=10006000 |title=Beschlu\u00df des Exekutivausschusses zur Inkraftsetzung des Schengener Durchf\u00fchrungs\u00fcbereinkommens in \u00d6sterreich |date=1997-10-07 |accessdate=2014-11-01}}</ref><ref name=acquis>{{cite journal |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:31999D0435&from=EN |title=Council Decision of 20 May 1999 concerning the definition of the Schengen acquis for the purpose of determining, in conformity with the relevant provisions of the Treaty establishing the European Community and the Treaty on European Union, the legal basis for each of the provisions or decisions which constitute the acquis |date=1999-07-10 |accessdate=2014-11-01 |journal=[[Official Journal of the European Union]] |volume=L |number=176/1}}</ref>{{refn|The elimination of border controls took place from 1 December 1997 to 31 March 1998.<ref name=austria/>|group=Note}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Belgium}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{nts|30528}}\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |{{UN_Population|Belgium}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|1985|6|14}}<ref name=origsign>{{cite web |url=https://verdragenbank.overheid.nl/en/Treaty/Details/000058.html |title=Agreement between the Governments of the States of the Benelux Economic Union, the Federal Republic of Germany and the French Republic on the Gradual Abolition of Checks at their Common Borders |accessdate=2014-10-31 |publisher=Government of the Netherlands}}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|1995|3|26}}<ref name=1995states>{{cite journal |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:41994D0029 |title=Decision of the Executive Committee of 22 December 1994 on bringing into force the Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement of 19 June 1990 |date=1994-12-22 |accessdate=2014-10-31 |journal=Official Journal of the European Union |volume=L |number=239/130}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flag|Czech Republic}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{nts|78866}}\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |{{UN_Population|Czechia}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|2003|4|16}}<ref name=2004enlarge/>\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|2007|12|21}}<ref name=2004states>{{cite journal |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32007D0801&from=EN |title=COUNCIL DECISION of 6 December 2007 on the full application of the provisions of the Schengen acquis in the Czech Republic, the Republic of Estonia, the Republic of Latvia, the Republic of Lithuania, the Republic of Hungary, the Republic of Malta, the Republic of Poland, the Republic of Slovenia and the Slovak Republic |date=2007-12-08 |accessdate=2014-10-27 |journal=Official Journal of the European Union |volume=L |number=323/34}}</ref>{{refn|For overland borders and [[Port|seaports]]; since 30 March 2008 also for airports.<ref name=2004states/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eu2008.si/en/News_and_Documents/Press_Releases/March/0325MNZschengen.html |publisher=Slovenia's EU Presidency |title=The final step of Schengen enlargement\u2014controls at internal air borders to be abolished in late March |date=25 March 2008}}</ref>|name=2004states|group=Note}}\n|-\n|{{flag|Denmark}} <br/>{{spaces|7}}<small>(excluding {{flag|Greenland}} and the {{flag|Faroe Islands}} which have open borders){{refn|Greenland and the Faroe Islands are not included in the Schengen area. However, persons travelling between the Faroe Islands, Greenland and the Schengen Area are not subject to border checks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:42000A0922(08)&from=EN |title=EUR-Lex - 42000A0922(08) - EN |publisher= }}</ref> The list of countries whose citizens require a visa for Greenland or the Faroe Islands is the same as for the Schengen Area,<ref>[http://naalakkersuisut.gl/en/About-government-of-greenland/About-Greenland/Coming-to-Greenland/Schengen-and-Tourists Schengen and Tourists], [[Government of Greenland]].</ref><ref>[http://www.government.fo/foreign-relations/visa-and-work-permit/ Visa and Work Permit], [[Government of the Faroe Islands]].</ref> but a Schengen visa will not allow the holder access to either territory, only a Danish visa stamped with either \"Valid for the Faroe Islands\" or \"Valid for Greenland\", or both.<ref name=\"greenland-faroe\">{{cite web |title=General Information on Schengen Short-Term Visas |publisher=Royal Danish Embassy in London |date=4 June 2009 |url=http://www.amblondon.um.dk/en/menu/consularservices/visas/shorttermvisas |accessdate=1 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100110021548/http://www.amblondon.um.dk/en/menu/ConsularServices/Visas/ShortTermVisas |archivedate=10 January 2010}}</ref>|group=Note}}</small>\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{nts|43094}}\n|style=\"text-align:right\" |{{UN_Population|Denmark}}\n|style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{dts|format=dmy|1996|12|19}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://verdragenbank.overhei